05352nam a22007335i 9780824847821DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248478217 a10.1515/97808248478212doi  a(DE-B1597)484627  a(OCoLC)890375271  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a307.3416095932231 aJohnson, Andrew Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGhosts of the New City :bSpirits, Urbanity, and the Ruins of Progress in Chiang Mai /cAndrew Alan Johnson; ed. by Rita Smith Kipp, David P. Chandler. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSoutheast Asia: Politics, Meaning, and Memory ;v6400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transcription -- tIntroduction: The Broken Building -- t1. Progress and Its Ruins -- t2. Foundations -- t3. Mediums -- t4. Lanna Style -- t5. Rebuilding Lanna -- tConclusion: The City Doesn’t Have a Future -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author -- tOther Volumes in the Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChiang Mai (literally, “new city”) suffered badly in the 1997 Asian financial crisis as the Northern Thai real estate bubble collapsed along with the Thai baht, crushing dreams of a renaissance of Northern prosperity. Years later, the ruins of the excesses of the 1990s still stain the skyline. In Ghosts of the New City, Andrew Alan Johnson shows how the trauma of the crash, brought back vividly by the political crisis of 2006, haunts efforts to remake the city. For many Chiang Mai residents, new developments harbor the seeds of the crash, which manifest themselves in anxious stories of ghosts and criminals who conceal themselves behind the city’s progressive veneer.Hopes for rebirth and fears of decline have their roots in Thai conceptions of progress, which draw from Buddhist and animist ideas of power and sacrality. Cities, Johnson argues, were centers where the charismatic power of kings and animist spirits were grounded; these entities assured progress by imbuing the space with sacred power that would avert disaster. Johnson traces such magico-religious conceptions of potency and space from historical records through present-day popular religious practice and draws parallels between these and secular attempts at urban revitalization. Through a detailed ethnography of the contested ways in which academics, urban activists, spirit mediums, and architects seek to revitalize the flagging economy and infrastructure of Chiang Mai, Johnson finds that alongside the hope for progress there exists a discourse about urban ghosts, deadly construction sites, and the lurking anxiety of another possible crash, a discourse that calls into question history’s upward trajectory. In this way, Ghosts of the New City draws new connections between urban history and popular religion that have implications far beyond Southeast Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHaunted placeszThailandzChiang Mai. 0aUrban renewalzThailandzChiang MaixPublic opinion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aChandler, David P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKipp, Rita Smith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z9783110752366